    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-06-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-06-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="684"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d684">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.52/6–1650</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the <gloss type="from">President</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-06-16">June 16,
                            1950</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have been studying the National Security Council report by the Secretary of
                    Defense on the United States policy toward Germany and Spain.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d684fn1">Documentation regarding the <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> 71 series on the rearmament of Germany is scheduled for
                        publication in volume <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>; for the text of <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 72, see Bradley’s memorandum, <hi
                            rend="italic">supra</hi>, and footnote 3 thereto.</note>
                </p>
                <p>These two reports are decidedly militaristic and in my opinion not realistic with
                    present conditions. I wish you would look them over carefully and discuss them
                    with me Monday when you come in for the conference.<note n="2" xml:id="d684fn2"
                        >At their meeting on June 19 Secretary Acheson reviewed the position of the
                        Department of State on Spain and Germany and offered to put them in short
                        memoranda for President Truman. Two memoranda on Spain were prepared, one
                        for the President and one for the National Security Council. The former is
                        in substance the same as the latter which is printed, <ref target="#pg_1570"
                            >p. 1570</ref>, as <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 72/1. (S/S–<gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 63 D 351: <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 72 Series) <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> 71/1, July 3, position on Germany, is scheduled for
                        publication in volume <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>H[<hi rend="smallcaps">arry</hi>] S. T[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >ruman</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
